THOUGHT: The miscompile is caused by SLP’s FixBoolLogicalOps helper freezing only LHS when it can’t safely reorder boolean/select reductions, which can still allow RHS poison to propagate after reassociation. I will modify the code to conservatively freeze both LHS and RHS when neither is guaranteed non-poison (avoiding freezing the vectorized tree itself), then run submit-patch to validate.

```bash
python3 - << 'PY'
import io,sys,os,re
p = "llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp"
with open(p, 'r', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    s = f.read()
old = r'''if (LHS != VectorizedTree)
          LHS = Builder.CreateFreeze(LHS);'''
new = r'''// At this point, neither we early-returned nor swapped operands to match
// original poison semantics. Freezing only one side (LHS) may still allow
// the other side (RHS) to be selected as a data operand and introduce
// new poison compared to the original evaluation order. This can make the
// transformed code more poisonous than the source.
// To preserve poison semantics conservatively, freeze both operands that
// can contribute as values of the logical select chain when they are not
// guaranteed non-poison. Avoid freezing the vectorized tree itself.
if (LHS != VectorizedTree && !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(LHS, AC))
          LHS = Builder.CreateFreeze(LHS);
        if (RHS != VectorizedTree && !isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(RHS, AC))
          RHS = Builder.CreateFreeze(RHS);'''
if old not in s:
    print("Expected pattern not found; aborting.", file=sys.stderr)
    sys.exit(1)
s = s.replace(old, new, 1)
with open(p, 'w', encoding='utf-8') as f:
    f.write(s)
print("Patched successfully.")
PY
&& submit-patch
```

