THOUGHT: The miscompilation arises because the SLPVectorizer freezes only the accumulator (VectorizedTree) during boolean/select reduction reassociation when neither operand is proven non-poison and swapping isn’t possible. This can still let the other operand (Res) be poison and make the transformation more poisonous than the source. I will conservatively freeze both operands in that fallback path in GetNewVectorizedTree to prevent introducing extra poison, then validate the patch.

```bash
perl -0777 -pe 'BEGIN{$found=0} if(!$found && /if\s*\(AnyBoolLogicOp\)\s*\{\s*.*?else\s*\{\s*VectorizedTree\s*=\s*Builder\.CreateFreeze\(VectorizedTree\);\s*\}\s*\}/s){ $_ =~ s/else\s*\{\s*VectorizedTree\s*=\s*Builder\.CreateFreeze\(VectorizedTree\);\s*\}/else {
            if (!isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(VectorizedTree, AC))
              VectorizedTree = Builder.CreateFreeze(VectorizedTree);
            if (!isGuaranteedNotToBePoison(Res, AC))
              Res = Builder.CreateFreeze(Res);
          }/; $found=1 } END{ if(!$found){ warn "Patch site not found
"; } }' -i llvm/lib/Transforms/Vectorize/SLPVectorizer.cpp && submit-patch
